  <li id="comment-43065" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/08130056569359560210" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Kristina</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2015/06/one-tuesday-late-morning/#comment-43065"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2015-06-14T01:19:28-04:00">Sunday, June 14, 2015 at 1:19 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I have been using this recipe for years, but my method has devolved into taking small bird out, not even rinsing since hearing NPR story that said rinsing just spreads bacteria around the kitchen and it&#39;s going In a hot even anyway, sprinkling with salt and roasting at high temperature.  So delicious.  We make this nearly once a week in the winter and now I&#39;ve mastered gravy with the pan drippings (spoon off dripping, reserve 1-2 at of fat, and mix with 1-2 T flour.  Add back to pan, stir on stovetop until bubbly, scraping up delicious bits, add a bit of chicken broth (small 8 oz. containers are perfect for this), stir until thickened and serve.  Reserve carcasses to make broth.</p>
<p>Regarding playing in car, if your car is old enough to have a CD player, beware of coins being inserted into CD drive.  We had a car with coins that rattled around and anytime we hit a bump the radio would turn off : )</p>
<p></p>
    </div>

